    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear F.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be obliged if you c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> inform your committee that am very unwilling to attend the deputation, as the excitement &amp; fatigue w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> almost certainly knock me up.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Nor w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> I attend, unless assured that the d. w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> recommend to G. beyond their advice by the R. Commiss, so that they may believe due regard not only for the interest <hi rend="italic">[</hi>of the<hi rend="italic">]</hi> lower animals, but of physiology interest of physiology which I believe to be to be of to be of utmost importance for the good of mankind, as well as with respect to the lower animals.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> My <hi rend="italic">[</hi>absence<hi rend="italic">]</hi> or <hi rend="italic">[</hi>presence<hi rend="italic">]</hi> I cann not believe that the <hi rend="italic">[</hi>presence<hi rend="italic">]</hi> as a member of the deputation can be of any importance &amp; therefore I hope that I may be excused.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> … that] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.3 to G.] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘no steps to’</note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n3">1.3 beyond … believe 1.5] <hi rend="italic">inter above del</hi> ‘but of physiology’</note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n4">1.4 they … believe] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n5">1.6 to be of] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘the most important &amp; useful’</note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n6">1.6 to be of utmost importance] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘all sciences’</note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n7">1.7 with respect to] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘the interests of’</note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n8">1.7 My <hi rend="italic">[</hi>absence<hi rend="italic">]</hi> or] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n9">1.7 cann] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘do’</note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n10">1.8 as … excused. 1.9] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘for my being of service w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be <hi rend="italic">[</hi>illeg<hi rend="italic">]</hi> in the <hi rend="italic">[</hi>illeg<hi rend="italic">]</hi> of the <hi rend="italic">[</hi>present<hi rend="italic">]</hi> of the smallest <hi rend="italic">[</hi>consequence<hi rend="italic">]</hi>’</note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the reference to the committee and deputation for legislation about vivisection (see nn. 2 and 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The committee of the Physiological Society was engaged in negotiations with government officials and MPs in charge of a bill in Parliament to regulate vivisection; the committee sent a delegation on 22 July to meet with <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1134.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Richard Assheton Cross</ref> (the home secretary) regarding possible amendments to the bill before it was debated in Parliament (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8863.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">French 1975</ref>, pp. 135–7, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8928.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sharpey-Schafer 1927</ref>, pp. 5–7, 40). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> was a member of the Physiological Society and CD was an honorary member (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8928.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sharpey-Schafer 1927</ref>, p. 13).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The Royal <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1031.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Commission on Vivisection</ref>, which met from June to December 1875, submitted a report in January 1876, recommending the conditions under which vivisection for physiological research and teaching should be permitted (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8615.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Report of the Royal Commission on vivisection</hi></ref>). CD had given testimony to the commission on 3 November 1875 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 23, Appendix VI).</note>
        </div>        
            
